<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	As of February&nbsp;29, 2016, there was no outstanding borrowings under the Credit Facility and the Company was in compliance with all of the
	limitations and requirements of the Credit Facility. As of February&nbsp;28, 2015, there was $9.6 million outstanding under the Credit Facility and the Company was in compliance with all of the limitations and requirements of the Credit Facility.
	Financing costs of $2.7&nbsp;million related to the Credit Facility have been capitalized and are being amortized over the term of the facility. For the years ended February&nbsp;29, 2016, February&nbsp;28, 2015 and February&nbsp;28, 2014, we
	recorded $0.7&nbsp;million, $0.9&nbsp;million and $1.0&nbsp;million of interest expense, respectively. For the years ended February&nbsp;29, 2016, February&nbsp;28, 2015 and February&nbsp;28, 2014, we recorded $0.1&nbsp;million, $0.3&nbsp;million
	and $0.4&nbsp;million of amortization of deferred financing costs related to the Credit Facility and Revolving Facility, respectively. The interest rates during the years ended February&nbsp;29, 2016, February&nbsp;28, 2015 and February&nbsp;28,
	2014 on the outstanding borrowings under the Credit Facility were 6.00%, 6.75% and 7.50%, respectively. During the years ended February 29, 2016 and February&nbsp;28, 2015, the average dollar amount of outstanding borrowings under the Credit
	Facility was $4.4 million and $6.0 million, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The Credit Facility contains limitations as to how borrowed funds may be used,
	such as restrictions on industry concentrations, asset size, weighted average life, currency denomination and collateral interests. The Credit Facility also includes certain requirements relating to portfolio performance, the violation of which
	could result in the limit of further advances and, in some cases, result in an event of default, allowing the lenders to accelerate repayment of amounts owed thereunder. The Credit Facility has an eight year term, consisting of a three year period
	(the &#147;Revolving Period&#148;), under which the Company may make and repay borrowings, and a final maturity five years from the end of the Revolving Period. Availability on the Credit Facility will be subject to a borrowing base calculation,
	based on, among other things, applicable advance rates (which vary from 50.0% to 75.0% of par or fair value depending on the type of loan asset) and the value of certain &#147;eligible&#148; loan assets included as part of the Borrowing Base. Funds
	may be borrowed at the greater of the prevailing LIBOR rate and 2.00%, plus an applicable margin of 5.50%. At the Company&#146;s option, funds may be borrowed based on an alternative base rate, which in no event will be less than 3.00%, and the
	applicable margin over such alternative base rate is 4.50%. In addition, the Company will pay the lenders a commitment fee of 0.75%&nbsp;per year on the unused amount of the Credit Facility for the duration of the Revolving Period.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	F-24
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage111"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D168943D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Our borrowing base under the Credit Facility was $21.8&nbsp;million subject to the Credit
	Facility cap of $45.0&nbsp;million at February&nbsp;29, 2016. For purposes of determining the borrowing base, most assets are assigned the values set forth in our most recent Annual Report on Form&nbsp;10-K or Quarterly Report on Form&nbsp;10-Q
	filed with the SEC. Accordingly, the February&nbsp;29, 2016 borrowing base relies upon the valuations set forth in the Quarterly Report on Form&nbsp;10-Q for the quarter ended November&nbsp;30, 2015. The valuations presented in this Annual Report on
	Form&nbsp;10-K will not be incorporated into the borrowing base until after this Annual Report on Form&nbsp;10-K is filed with the SEC.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	SBA
	Debentures
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	SBIC LP is able to borrow funds from the SBA against regulatory capital (which approximates equity capital) that is
	paid in and is subject to customary regulatory requirements including but not limited to an examination by the SBA. As of February&nbsp;29, 2016, we have funded SBIC LP with $75.0&nbsp;million of equity capital, and have $103.7&nbsp;million of
	SBA-guaranteed debentures outstanding. SBA debentures are non-recourse to us, have a 10-year maturity, and may be prepaid at any time without penalty. The interest rate of SBA debentures is fixed at the time of issuance, often referred to as
	pooling, at a market-driven spread over 10-year U.S. Treasury Notes. SBA current regulations limit the amount that SBIC LP may borrow to a maximum of $150.0&nbsp;million, which is up to twice its potential regulatory capital.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	SBICs are designed to stimulate the flow of private equity capital to eligible small businesses. Under SBA regulations, SBICs may make loans
	to eligible small businesses and invest in the equity securities of small businesses. Under present SBA regulations, eligible small businesses include businesses that have a tangible net worth not exceeding $19.5&nbsp;million and have average annual
	fully taxed net income not exceeding $6.5&nbsp;million for the two most recent fiscal years. In addition, an SBIC must devote 25.0% of its investment activity to &#145;&#145;smaller&#146;&#146; concerns as defined by the SBA. A smaller concern is
	one that has a tangible net worth not exceeding $6.0&nbsp;million and has average annual fully taxed net income not exceeding $2.0&nbsp;million for the two most recent fiscal years. SBA regulations also provide alternative size standard criteria to
	determine eligibility, which depend on the industry in which the business is engaged and are based on such factors as the number of employees and gross sales. According to SBA regulations, SBICs may make long-term loans to small businesses, invest
	in the equity securities of such businesses and provide them with consulting and advisory services.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	SBIC LP is subject to regulation and
	oversight by the SBA, including requirements with respect to maintaining certain minimum financial ratios and other covenants. Receipt of an SBIC license does not assure that SBIC LP will receive SBA guaranteed debenture funding, which is dependent
	upon SBIC LP continuing to be in compliance with SBA regulations and policies. The SBA, as a creditor, will have a superior claim to SBIC LP&#146;s assets over our stockholders and debtholders in the event we liquidate SBIC LP or the SBA exercises
	its remedies under the SBA-guaranteed debentures issued by SBIC LP upon an event of default.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The Company received exemptive relief from
	the Securities and Exchange Commission to permit it to exclude the debt of SBIC LP guaranteed by the SBA from the definition of senior securities in the 200.0% asset coverage test under the 1940 Act. This allows the Company increased flexibility
	under the 200.0% asset coverage test by permitting it to borrow up to $150.0&nbsp;million more than it would otherwise be able to absent the receipt of this exemptive relief.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	As of February&nbsp;29, 2016 and February&nbsp;28, 2015, there was $103.7&nbsp;million and $79.0 million outstanding of SBA debentures,
	respectively. The carrying amount of the amount outstanding of SBA debentures approximates its fair value, which is based on a waterfall analysis showing adequate collateral coverage, $3.6&nbsp;million, of financing costs related to the SBA
	debentures, have been capitalized and are being amortized over the term of the commitment and drawdown. For the years ended February&nbsp;29, 2016, February&nbsp;28, 2015 and February 28, 2014 we recorded $2.6&nbsp;million, $2.0&nbsp;million and
	$1.3 million of interest expense related to the SBA debentures, respectively. For the years ended February&nbsp;29, 2016, February&nbsp;28, 2015 and February 28, 2014, we recorded $0.4&nbsp;million, $0.3&nbsp;million and $0.2 million of amortization
	of deferred financing costs related to the SBA debentures, respectively. The weighted average interest rate during the years ended February&nbsp;29, 2016 and February&nbsp;28, 2015 on the outstanding borrowings of the SBA debentures was 3.12% and
	2.93%, respectively. During the years ended February&nbsp;29, 2016 and February&nbsp;28, 2015, the average dollar amount of SBA debentures outstanding was $83.0 million and $67.9 million, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In December 2015, the 2016 omnibus spending bill approved by Congress and signed into law by the President increased the amount of
	SBA-guaranteed debentures that affiliated SBIC funds can have outstanding from $225.0 million to $350.0 million, subject to SBA approval. SBA regulations currently limit the amount of SBA-guaranteed debentures that an SBIC may issue to
	$150.0&nbsp;million when it has at least $75.0&nbsp;million in regulatory capital. Affiliated SBICs are permitted to issue up to a combined maximum amount of $350.0&nbsp;million in SBA-guaranteed debentures when they have at least
	$175.0&nbsp;million in combined regulatory capital.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On April&nbsp;2, 2015, the SBA issued a &#147;green light&#148; or &#147;go
	forth&#148; letter inviting us to continue our application process to obtain a license to form and operate its second SBIC subsidiary. If approved, a second SBIC license would provide us an incremental source of long-term capital by permitting us to
	issue up to $150 million of additional SBA-guaranteed debentures in addition to the $150 million
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	F-25
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage112"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D168943D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	already approved under the first license. Receipt of a green light letter from the SBA does not assure an applicant that the SBA will ultimately issue an SBIC license and we have received no
	assurance or indication from the SBA that it will receive an SBIC license, or of the timeframe in which it would receive a license, should one be granted.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Notes
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On May&nbsp;10, 2013, the
	Company issued $42.0 million in aggregate principal amount of 7.50% fixed-rate notes due 2020 (the &#147;Notes&#148;).&nbsp;The Notes will mature on May&nbsp;31, 2020, and may be redeemed in whole or in part at any time or from time to time at the
	Company&#146;s option on or after May&nbsp;31, 2016.&nbsp;Interest will be payable quarterly beginning August&nbsp;15, 2013.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On
	May&nbsp;17, 2013, the Company closed an additional $6.3&nbsp;million in aggregate principal amount of the Notes, pursuant to the full exercise of the underwriters&#146; option to purchase additional Notes. On May&nbsp;29, 2015, the Company entered
	into a Debt Distribution Agreement with Landenburg Thalmann&nbsp;&amp; Co. through which the Company may offer for sale, from time to time, up to $20.0 million in aggregate principal amount of the Notes through an At-the-Market (&#147;ATM&#148;)
	offering. As of February&nbsp;29, 2016, the Company sold 539,725 bonds with a principal of $13,493,125 at an average price of $25.31 for aggregate net proceeds of $13,385,766 (net of transaction costs).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	As of February&nbsp;29, 2016, the carrying amount and fair value of the Notes was $61.8&nbsp;million and $60.2&nbsp;million, respectively. The
	fair value of the Notes, which are publicly traded, is based upon closing market quotes as of the measurement date and would be classified as a level 1 liability within the fair value hierarchy. As of February&nbsp;29, 2016, $2.7&nbsp;million of
	financing costs related to the Notes (including underwriting commissions and net of issuance premiums) have been capitalized and are being amortized over the term of the Notes. For the year ended February&nbsp;29, 2016, we recorded $4.3&nbsp;million
	of interest expense and $0.4 million of amortization of deferred financing costs related to the Notes. As of February&nbsp;28, 2015, the carrying amount and fair value of the Notes was $48.3&nbsp;million and $49.8&nbsp;million, respectively. As of
	February&nbsp;28, 2015, $2.5&nbsp;million of financing costs related to the Notes have been capitalized and are being amortized over the term of the Notes. For the years ended February 28, 2015 and February 28, 2014, we recorded $3.6 million and
	$2.9 million of interest expense, respectively, and $0.3 million and $0.3 million, respectively, of amortization of deferred financing costs related to the Notes. During the years ended February&nbsp;29, 2016 and February&nbsp;28, 2015, the average
	dollar amount of Notes outstanding was $55.7 million and $48.3 million, respectively.
</P>

	Off-balance sheet arrangements

	The Company&#146;s off-balance sheet arrangements consisted of $2.0&nbsp;million and $11.2&nbsp;million of unfunded commitments to provide debt
	financing to its portfolio companies or to fund limited partnership interests as of February&nbsp;29, 2016 and February&nbsp;28, 2015, respectively. Such commitments are generally up to the Company&#146;s discretion to approve, or the satisfaction
	of certain financial and nonfinancial covenants and involve, to varying degrees, elements of credit risk in excess of the amount recognized in the Company&#146;s consolidated statements of assets and liabilities and are not reflected in the

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Note&nbsp;9. Directors Fees
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The independent directors receive an annual fee of $40,000. They also receive $2,500 plus reimbursement of reasonable out-of-pocket expenses
	incurred in connection with attending each board meeting and receive $1,000 plus reimbursement of reasonable out-of-pocket expenses incurred in connection with attending each committee meeting. In addition, the chairman of the Audit Committee
	receives an annual fee of $5,000 and the chairman of each other committee receives an annual fee of $2,000 for their additional services in these capacities. In addition, we have purchased directors&#146; and officers&#146; liability insurance on
	behalf of our directors and officers. Independent directors have the option to receive their directors&#146; fees in the form of our common stock issued at a price per share equal to the greater of net asset value or the market price at the time of
	payment. No compensation is paid to directors who are &#147;interested persons&#148; of the Company (as such term is defined in the 1940 Act). For the years ended February&nbsp;29, 2016, February&nbsp;28, 2015 and February&nbsp;28, 2014, we accrued
	$0.2&nbsp;million, $0.2&nbsp;million, and $0.2&nbsp;million for directors&#146; fees expense, respectively. As of February&nbsp;29, 2016 and February&nbsp;28, 2015, $0.03&nbsp;million and $0.03&nbsp;million in directors&#146; fees expense were
	unpaid and included in accounts payable and accrued expenses in the consolidated statements of assets and liabilities. As of February&nbsp;29, 2016, we had not issued any common stock to our directors as compensation for their services.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Note&nbsp;10. Stockholders&#146; Equity
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On May&nbsp;16, 2006, GSC Group,&nbsp;Inc. capitalized the&nbsp;LLC, by contributing $1,000 in exchange for 67&nbsp;shares, constituting all of
	the issued and outstanding shares of the&nbsp;LLC.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On March&nbsp;20, 2007, the Company issued 95,995.5 and 8,136.2 shares of common
	stock, priced at $150.00 per share, to GSC Group and certain individual employees of GSC Group, respectively, in exchange for the general partnership interest and a limited partnership interest in GSC Partners CDO&nbsp;III&nbsp;GP,&nbsp;LP,
	collectively valued at $15.6&nbsp;million. At this time, the 6.7&nbsp;shares owned by GSC Group in the&nbsp;LLC were exchanged for 6.7&nbsp;shares of the Company.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On March&nbsp;28, 2007, the Company completed its IPO of 725,000 shares of common stock, priced at $150.00 per share, before underwriting
	discounts and commissions. Total proceeds received from the IPO, net of $7.1&nbsp;million in underwriter&#146;s discount and commissions, and $1.0&nbsp;million in offering costs, were $100.7&nbsp;million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On November&nbsp;13, 2009, we declared a dividend of $18.25 per share payable on December&nbsp;31, 2009. Shareholders had the option to
	receive payment of the dividend in cash, shares of common stock, or a combination of cash and shares of common stock, provided that the aggregate cash payable to all shareholders was limited to $2.1&nbsp;million or $2.50 per share. Based on
	shareholder elections, the dividend consisted of $2.1&nbsp;million in cash and 864,872.5 of newly issued shares of common stock.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On
	July&nbsp;30, 2010, our Manager and its affiliates purchased 986,842 shares of common stock at $15.20 per share. Total proceeds received from this sale were $15.0&nbsp;million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On August&nbsp;12, 2010, we effected a one-for-ten reverse stock split of our outstanding common stock. As a result of the reverse stock
	split, every ten shares of our common stock were converted into one share of our common stock. Any fractional shares received as a result of the reverse stock split were redeemed for cash. The total cash payment in lieu of shares was $230.
	Immediately after the reverse stock split, we had 2,680,842 shares of our common stock outstanding.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On November&nbsp;12, 2010, we
	declared a dividend of $4.40 per share payable on December&nbsp;29, 2010. Shareholders had the option to receive payment of the dividend in cash, shares of common stock, or a combination of cash and shares of common stock, provided that the
	aggregate cash payable to all shareholders was limited to approximately $1.2&nbsp;million or $0.44 per share. Based on shareholder elections, the dividend consisted of approximately $1.2&nbsp;million in cash and 596,235 shares of common stock.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On November&nbsp;15, 2011, we declared a dividend of $3.00 per share payable on December&nbsp;30, 2011. Shareholders had the option to receive
	payment of the dividend in cash, shares of common stock, or a combination of cash and shares of common stock, provided that the aggregate cash payable to all shareholders was limited to approximately $2.0&nbsp;million or $0.60 per share. Based on
	shareholder elections, the dividend consisted of approximately $2.0&nbsp;million in cash and 599,584 shares of common stock.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	F-27
</P>

	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On November&nbsp;9, 2012, the Company declared a dividend of $4.25 per share payable on
	December&nbsp;31, 2012. Shareholders had the option to receive payment of the dividend in cash, shares of common stock, or a combination of cash and shares of common stock, provided that the aggregate cash payable to all shareholders was limited to
	approximately $3.3&nbsp;million or $0.85 per share. Based on shareholder elections, the dividend consisted of approximately $3.3&nbsp;million in cash and 853,455 shares of common stock.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On October&nbsp;30, 2013, the Company declared a dividend of $2.65 per share payable on December&nbsp;27, 2013. Shareholders had the option to
	receive payment of the dividend in cash, shares of common stock, or a combination of cash and shares of common stock, provided that the aggregate cash payable to all shareholders was limited to approximately $2.5&nbsp;million or $0.53 per share.
	Based on shareholder elections, the dividend consisted of approximately $2.5&nbsp;million in cash and 649,500 shares of common stock.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On
	September&nbsp;24, 2014, the Company declared a dividend of $0.18 per share payable on November&nbsp;28, 2014. Shareholders had the option to receive payment of the dividend in cash, or receive shares of common stock pursuant to the Company&#146;s
	DRIP. Based on shareholder elections, the dividend consisted of approximately $0.6&nbsp;million in cash and 22,283 newly issued shares of common stock.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On September&nbsp;24, 2014, the Company declared a dividend of $0.22 per share payable on February&nbsp;27, 2015. Shareholders had the option
	to receive payment of the dividend in cash, or receive shares of common stock, pursuant our DRIP. Based on shareholder elections, the dividend consisted of approximately $0.8&nbsp;million in cash and 26,858 newly issued shares of common stock.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On September&nbsp;24, 2014, the Company announced the approval of an open market share repurchase plan that allowed it to repurchase up to
	200,000 shares of its common stock at prices below its NAV as reported in its then most recently published consolidated financial statements. As of February 29, 2016, the Company purchased 25,417 shares of common stock, at the average price of
	$14.03, for approximately $0.4 million pursuant to this repurchase plan. On October&nbsp;7, 2015, the Company&#146;s board of directors extended the open market share repurchase plan for another year and increased the number of shares the Company is
	permitted to repurchase at prices below its NAV, as reported in its then most recently published consolidated financial statements, to 400,000 shares of its common stock.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On April&nbsp;9, 2015, the Company declared a dividend of $0.27 per share payable on May&nbsp;29, 2015. Shareholders had the option to receive
	payment of the dividend in cash, or receive shares of common stock, pursuant our DRIP. Based on shareholder elections, the dividend consisted of approximately $0.9&nbsp;million in cash and 33,766 newly issued shares of common stock.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On May&nbsp;14, 2015, the Company declared a special dividend of $1.00 per share payable on June&nbsp;5, 2015. Shareholders had the option to
	receive payment of the dividend in cash, or receive shares of common stock, pursuant our DRIP. Based on shareholder elections, the dividend consisted of approximately $3.4&nbsp;million in cash and 126,230 newly issued shares of common stock.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On July&nbsp;8, 2015, the Company declared a dividend of $0.33 per share payable on August&nbsp;31, 2015. Shareholders had the option to
	receive payment of the dividend in cash, or receive shares of common stock, pursuant our DRIP. Based on shareholder elections, the dividend consisted of approximately $1.1&nbsp;million in cash and 47,861 newly issued shares of common stock.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On October&nbsp;7, 2015, the Company declared a dividend of $0.36 per share payable on November&nbsp;30, 2015. Shareholders had the option to
	receive payment of the dividend in cash, or receive shares of common stock, pursuant our DRIP. Based on shareholder elections, the dividend consisted of approximately $1.1&nbsp;million in cash and 61,029 newly issued shares of common stock.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On January 12, 2016, the Company declared a dividend of $0.40 per share payable on February 29, 2016. Shareholders had the option to receive
	payment of the dividend in cash, or receive shares of common stock, pursuant our DRIP. Based on shareholder elections, the dividend consisted of approximately $1.4&nbsp;million in cash and 66,764 newly issued shares of common stock.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Note&nbsp;11. Earnings Per Share
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In
	accordance with the provisions of FASB ASC 260, &#147;Earnings per Share&#148; (&#147;ASC 260&#148;), basic earnings per share is computed by dividing earnings available to common shareholders by the weighted average number of shares outstanding
	during the period. Other potentially dilutive common shares, and the related impact to earnings, are considered when calculating earnings per share on a diluted basis.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Note&nbsp;12. Dividend
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On January&nbsp;12, 2016, the Company&#146;s board of directors declared a dividend of $0.40 per share payable on February 29, 2016, to all
	stockholders of record on February&nbsp;1, 2016. Shareholders had the option to receive payment of the dividend in cash, or receive shares of common stock, pursuant the Company&#146;s DRIP.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Based on shareholder elections, the dividend consisted of approximately $1.4 million in cash and 66,764 newly issued shares of common stock,
	or 1.2% of the Company&#146;s outstanding common stock prior to the dividend payment. The number of shares of common stock comprising the stock portion was calculated based on a price of $13.11 per share, which equaled the volume weighted average
	trading price per share of the common stock on February&nbsp;16, 17, 18, 19, 22, 23, 24, 25, 26 and 29, 2016.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On October&nbsp;7, 2015,
	the Company&#146;s board of directors declared a dividend of $0.36 per share payable on November&nbsp;30, 2015, to common stockholders of record on November&nbsp;2, 2015. Shareholders had the option to receive payment of the dividend in cash, or
	receive shares of common stock, pursuant the Company&#146;s DRIP.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Based on shareholder elections, the dividend consisted of approximately
	$1.1&nbsp;million in cash and 61,029 newly issued shares of common stock, or 1.1% of the Company&#146;s outstanding common stock prior to the dividend payment. The number of shares of common stock comprising the stock portion was calculated based on
	a price of $14.53 per share, which equaled the volume weighted average trading price per share of the common stock on November&nbsp;16, 17, 18, 19, 20, 23, 24, 25, 27 and 30, 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On July&nbsp;8, 2015, the Company&#146;s board of directors declared a dividend of $0.33 per share payable on August&nbsp;31, 2015, to common
	stockholders of record on August 3, 2015. Shareholders had the option to receive payment of the dividend in cash, or receive shares of common stock, pursuant the Company&#146;s DRIP.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Based on shareholder elections, the dividend consisted of approximately $1.1&nbsp;million in cash and 47,861 newly issued shares of common
	stock, or 0.9% of the Company&#146;s outstanding common stock prior to the dividend payment. The number of shares of common stock comprising the stock portion was calculated based on a price of $15.28 per share, which equaled the volume weighted
	average trading price per share of the common stock on August&nbsp;18, 19, 20, 21, 24, 25, 26, 27, 28 and 31, 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On May&nbsp;14, 2015,
	the Company&#146;s board of directors declared a special dividend of $1.00 per share payable on June&nbsp;5, 2015, to common stockholders of record on May 26, 2015. Shareholders had the option to receive payment of the dividend in cash, or receive
	shares of common stock, pursuant the Company&#146;s DRIP.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Based on shareholder elections, the dividend consisted of approximately
	$3.4&nbsp;million in cash and 126,230 newly issued shares of common stock, or 2.3% of the Company&#146;s outstanding common stock prior to the dividend payment. The number of shares of common stock comprising the stock portion was calculated based
	on a price of $16.47 per share, which equaled the volume weighted average trading price per share of the common stock on May&nbsp;22, 26, 27, 28, 29 and June 1, 2, 3, 4, and 5, 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On April&nbsp;9, 2015, the Company&#146;s board of directors declared a dividend of $0.27 per share payable on May&nbsp;29, 2015, to common
	stockholders of record on May 4, 2015. Shareholders had the option to receive payment of the dividend in cash, or receive shares of common stock, pursuant the Company&#146;s DRIP.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Based on shareholder elections, the dividend consisted of approximately $0.9&nbsp;million in cash and 33,766 newly issued shares of common
	stock, or 0.6% of the Company&#146;s outstanding common stock prior to the dividend payment. The number of shares of common stock comprising the stock portion was calculated based on a price of $16.78 per share, which equaled the volume weighted
	average trading price per share of the common stock on May&nbsp;15, 18, 19, 20, 21, 22, 26, 27, 28 and 29, 2015.

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On September&nbsp;24,
	2014, the Company declared a dividend of $0.22 per share payable on February&nbsp;27, 2015. Shareholders have the option to receive payment of the dividend in cash, or receive shares of common stock pursuant to the Company&#146;s DRIP. Based on
	shareholder elections, the dividend consisted of approximately $0.8&nbsp;million in cash and 26,858 newly issued shares of common stock, or 0.5% of our outstanding common stock prior to the dividend payment. The number of shares of common stock
	comprising the stock portion was calculated based on a price of $14.97 per share, which equaled the volume weighted average trading price per share of the common stock on February&nbsp;13, 17, 18, 19, 20, 23, 24, 25, 26 and 27, 2015.

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On September&nbsp;24, 2014, the Company declared a dividend of $0.18 per share payable on
	November&nbsp;28, 2014. Shareholders had the option to receive payment of the dividend in cash, or receive shares of common stock pursuant to the Company&#146;s DRIP. Based on shareholder elections, the dividend consisted of approximately
	$0.6&nbsp;million in cash and 22,283 newly issued shares of common stock, or 0.4% of our outstanding common stock prior to the dividend payment. The number of shares of common stock comprising the stock portion was calculated based on a price of
	$14.37 per share, which equaled the volume weighted average trading price per share of the common stock on November&nbsp;14, 17, 18, 19, 20, 21, 24, 25, 26 and 28, 2014.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On October&nbsp;30, 2013, the Company declared a dividend of $2.65 per share payable on December&nbsp;27, 2013. Shareholders had the option to
	receive payment of the dividend in cash, shares of common stock, or a combination of cash and shares of common stock, provided that the aggregate cash payable to all shareholders was limited to approximately $2.5&nbsp;million or $0.53 per share.
	This dividend was declared in reliance on certain private letter rulings issued by the IRS concluding that a RIC may treat a distribution of its own stock as fulfilling its RIC distribution requirements if each stockholder may elect to receive his
	or her entire distribution in either cash or stock of the RIC subject to a limitation on the aggregate amount of cash to be distributed to all stockholders, which limitation must be at least 20.0% of the aggregate declared distribution.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Based on shareholder elections, the dividend consisted of approximately $2.5&nbsp;million in cash and 649,500 shares of common stock, or 13.7%
	of our outstanding common stock prior to the dividend payment. The number of shares of common stock comprising the stock portion was calculated based on a price of $15.439 per share, which equaled the volume weighted average trading price per share
	of the common stock on December&nbsp;11, 13, and 16, 2013.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On November&nbsp;9, 2012, the Company declared a dividend of $4.25 per share
	payable on December&nbsp;31, 2012. Shareholders had the option to receive payment of the dividend in cash, shares of common stock, or a combination of cash and shares of common stock, provided that the aggregate cash payable to all shareholders was
	limited to approximately $3.3&nbsp;million or $0.85 per share.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Based on shareholder elections, the dividend consisted of approximately
	$3.3&nbsp;million in cash and 853,455 shares of common stock, or 22.0% of our outstanding common stock prior to the dividend payment. The amount of cash elected to be received was greater than the cash limit of 20.0% of the aggregate dividend
	amount, thus resulting in the payment of a combination of cash and stock to shareholders who elected to receive cash. The number of shares of common stock comprising the stock portion was calculated based on a price of $15.444 per share, which
	equaled the volume weighted average trading price per share of the common stock on December&nbsp;14, 17, and 19, 2012.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On
	November&nbsp;15, 2011, the Company declared a dividend of $3.00 per share payable on December&nbsp;30, 2011. Shareholders had the option to receive payment of the dividend in cash, shares of common stock, or a combination of cash and shares of
	common stock, provided that the aggregate cash payable to all shareholders was limited to approximately $2.0&nbsp;million or $0.60 per share.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Based on shareholder elections, the dividend consisted of approximately $2.0&nbsp;million in cash and 599,584 shares of common stock, or 18.0%
	of our outstanding common stock prior to the dividend payment. The amount of cash elected to be received was greater than the cash limit of 20.0% of the aggregate dividend amount, thus resulting in the payment of a combination of cash and stock to
	shareholders who elected to receive cash. The number of shares of common stock comprising the stock portion was calculated based on a price of $13.1171 per share, which equaled the volume weighted average trading price per share of the common stock
	on December&nbsp;20, 21 and 22, 2011.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On November&nbsp;12, 2010, the Company declared a dividend of $4.40 per share payable on
	December&nbsp;23, 2010. Shareholders had the option to receive payment of the dividend in cash, shares of common stock, or a combination of cash and shares of common stock, provided that the aggregate cash payable to all shareholders was limited to
	approximately $1.2&nbsp;million or $0.44 per share.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Based on shareholder elections, the dividend consisted of approximately
	$1.2&nbsp;million in cash and 596,235 shares of common stock, or 22.0% of our outstanding common stock prior to the dividend payment. The amount of cash elected to be received was greater than the cash limit of 10.0% of the aggregate dividend
	amount, thus resulting in the payment of a combination of cash and stock to shareholders who elected to receive cash. The number of shares of common stock comprising the stock portion was calculated based on a price of $17.8049 per share, which
	equaled the volume weighted average trading price per share of the common stock on December&nbsp;20, 21 and 22, 2010. The consolidated financial statements for the period ended November&nbsp;30, 2010 have been retroactively adjusted to reflect the
	increase in common stock as a result of the dividend in accordance with the provisions of ASC&nbsp;505-20-S50 regarding disclosure of a capital structure change after the interim balance sheet but before the release of the financial statements.
</P>

	As described in Note 2 to the consolidated financial statements and notes thereto, we identified errors that
	impacted the years ended February&nbsp;28, 2014,&nbsp;February&nbsp;28, 2013&nbsp;and February&nbsp;29, 2012. The corrections for the errors, which we have concluded are immaterial to all prior period consolidated financial statements, are reflected
	in the consolidated financial statements and selected financial data included in this Form 10-K.

	&nbsp;

<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	(1)
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	Net investment income per share is calculated using the weighted average shares outstanding during the period.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;

<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D168943D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	(2)
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	Total investment return is calculated assuming a purchase of common shares at the current market value on the first day and a sale at the current market value on the last day of the periods reported. Dividends and
	distributions, if any, are assumed for purposes of this calculation to be reinvested at prices obtained under the Company&#146;s dividend reinvestment plan. Total investment return does not reflect brokerage commissions. Total investment returns
	covering less than a full period are not annualized.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	(3)
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	Total investment return is calculated assuming a purchase of common shares at the current net asset value on the first day and a sale at the current net asset value on the last day of the periods reported. Dividends and
	distributions, if any, are assumed for purposes of this calculation to be reinvested at prices obtained under the Company&#146;s dividend reinvestment plan. Total investment return does not reflect brokerage commissions.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	(4)
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	Represents the dilutive effect of issuing common stock below net asset value per share during the period in connection with the satisfaction of the Company&#146;s annual RIC distribution requirement. See Note 12,
	Dividend.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	(5)
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	Portfolio turnover rate is calculated using the lesser of year-to-date sales or year-to-date purchases over the average of the invested assets at fair value.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<EFX_SUBSEQUENT_EVENTS>
<A NAME="FIS_SUBSEQUENT_EVENTS"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Note&nbsp;15. Subsequent Events
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The Company has evaluated subsequent events through the filing of this Form 10-K and determined that there have been no events that
	have occurred that would require adjustments to the Company&#146;s disclosures in the consolidated financial statements except for the following:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On March 31, 2016, the Company declared a dividend of $0.41 per share payable on April 27, 2016, to common stockholders of record on April 15,
	2016. Shareholders had the option to receive payment of the dividend in cash, or receive shares of common stock, pursuant our DRIP. Based on shareholder elections, the dividend consisted of approximately $1.5 million in cash and 56,728 newly issued
	shares of common stock, or 1.0% of our outstanding common stock prior to the dividend payment. The number of shares of common stock comprising the stock portion was calculated based on a price of $15.43 per share, which equaled the volume weighted
	average trading price per share of the common stock on April&nbsp;14, 15, 18, 19, 20, 21, 22, 25, 26 and 27, 2016.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>

	F-34

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:24PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
<B>
<U>
	IMPORTANT NOTE
</U>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In accordance with certain SEC rules, Saratoga Investment Corp. (the &#147;Company&#148;) is providing additional information regarding one of
	its portfolio companies, Saratoga Investment Corp. CLO 2013-1,&nbsp;Ltd. (&#147;Saratoga CLO&#148;). The Company owns 100% of the subordinated notes of the Saratoga CLO. The additional financial information regarding the Saratoga CLO does not
	directly impact the Company&#146;s financial position, results of operations or cash flows.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	S-1
</P>

<EFX_AUDITORS_OPINION>
<A NAME="FIS_AUDITORS_OPINION_3"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
<B>
</B>
<B>
<I>
</I>
</B>
<B>
<A NAME="D168943D10K_HTM_TX168943_35">
</A>
	Report of Independent Auditors
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The Collateral Manager and Directors,
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Saratoga Investment Corp.
	CLO 2013-1, Ltd.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We have audited the accompanying financial statements of Saratoga Investment Corp. CLO 2013-1, Ltd., which comprise the
	statements of assets and liabilities, including the schedules of investments, as of February 29, 2016 and February 28, 2015, and the statements of operations, changes in net assets and cash flows for the years ended February 29, 2016, February 28,
	2015 and February 28, 2014, and the related notes to the financial statements.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
</B>
<B>
<I>
</I>
</B>
<B>
	Management&#146;s Responsibility for the Financial
	Statements
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
</I>
</B>
	Management is responsible for the preparation and fair presentation of these financial statements in
	conformity with U.S. generally accepted accounting principles; this includes the design, implementation, and maintenance of internal control relevant to the preparation and fair presentation of financial statements that are free of material
	misstatement, whether due to fraud or error.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
</B>
<B>
<I>
</I>
</B>
<B>
	Auditor&#146;s Responsibility
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Our responsibility is to express an opinion on these financial statements based on our audits. We conducted our audits in accordance with
	auditing standards generally accepted in the United States. Those standards require that we plan and perform the audit to obtain reasonable assurance about whether the financial statements are free of material misstatement.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	An audit involves performing procedures to obtain audit evidence about the amounts and disclosures in the financial statements. The procedures
	selected depend on the auditor&#146;s judgment, including the assessment of the risks of material misstatement of the financial statements, whether due to fraud or error. In making those risk assessments, the auditor considers internal control
	relevant to the entity&#146;s preparation and fair presentation of the financial statements in order to design audit procedures that are appropriate in the circumstances, but not for the purpose of expressing an opinion on the effectiveness of the
	entity&#146;s internal control. Accordingly, we express no such opinion.&nbsp;An audit also includes evaluating the appropriateness of accounting policies used and the reasonableness of significant accounting estimates made by management, as well as
	evaluating the overall presentation of the financial statements.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We believe that the audit evidence we have obtained is sufficient and
	appropriate to provide a basis for our audit&nbsp;opinion.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Opinion
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In our opinion, the financial statements referred to above present fairly, in all material respects, the financial position of Saratoga
	Investment Corp. CLO 2013-1, Ltd. at February 29, 2016 and February 28, 2015, and the results of its operations, changes in its net assets and its cash flows for the years ended February 29, 2016, February 28, 2015 and February 28, 2014, in
	conformity with U.S. generally accepted accounting principles.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	/s/ Ernst &amp; Young
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	New York, New York
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	May 17, 2016
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	S-2
